    - task (Task): The task sent to the miner.
    - responses (List[float]): A list of responses from the miner.

[bold]Total possible reward:[/bold] {max_possible_score}

(on testnet)

So the math works like this -
1) You register your miner and get a new uid - "scores" (internally what a validator tracks for a miner) are set to 0 on all active, participating (non-weight-copying) validators, and your immunity is set to 5000 blocks (16 hours or so)
2) Each validator tracks scores on their own for your uid.
3) Those scores are weighted with each iteration at 0.05 (alpha) for most recent score and 0.95 (1-alpha) for existing average score (starts at 0.00), these are summed together.  So if your first score is a 1.00, your score for that validator will become 0.05, which is tiny and won't help with incentive/emissions.
4) It takes about 45 scores of 1.0 to get your score with a single validator to the 0.9 range where you become more competitive in the subnet as a miner.
5) Validators query about 11 miners at random each step they run - that's 11 miners of a pool of 220+ miners - so every 20 steps a validator takes (on average), they will hit the same miner (of course it's random and will vary).
6) Now you need to know the rate at which the validator is operating - how many tasks do they send out in a given time frame?  (that's something you can track and it varies per validator b/c of hardware, internet/latency, etc.)
7) Even though you see a LOT of tasks coming in and you're getting ok scores, divide that by the number of validators that task you and it's only 5 task per validator (there are 16 registered validators on this subnet, not all are active) which is not enough really to budge your score with that validator, especially if your scores are not ALL nearly 1.0s.

The question now is - for each validator, will you see 45 steps (to get you to 0.9 (assuming perfect scoring)) and score 1.0 for all those steps before the immunity runs out?

If you want to triple check the scores and what that might mean in terms of weights (note score and weight will differ b/c weight is normalized across the subnet, score is just between your miner and the validator that tasked you), you can start at 0.00 when your first task comes in for a given validator, take the normalized reward (score) and do the math per validator. 

In your case @CrypτicMax [τ,τ], you are going to want to focus on and fix your low scores, those are really hurting your chances.

Even with perfects scores and at the rate that validators are operating, you aren't reaching 0.9 in 16 hours on average.  Some miners get lucky and get tasked more frequently than average (b/c random) which sends them sailing.  Others don't see hits at all for a while, or have to fix an error and are severely penalized for downtime, or they just get unlucky and aren't hit as frequently (b/c random).

We are looking at changing a few things ... 
1) instead of sampling 11 miners at a time, we're looking to roughly double this to 25 and instead of getting hits every 20ish steps, it's be more like every 8-10 steps
2) instead of starting at 0 and having to claw your way back during immunity, maybe it starts at 0.25 or 0.55
3) instead of 0.05 as the alpha weighting, maybe it's 0.1 or 0.075 to speed up the rate at which new scores influence the average score
4) instead of 5000 blocks of immunity, maybe it's longer - this is my least favorite b/c it means more miners are immune and thus higher performing miners are pruned

I don't like messing with these options, but because of the way these factors are set, I have seen several really good miners get pruned with near perfect scores.
My favorite is just increasing the workload on the validator to task more miners.
We will likely find the right combo and push an update with the new tasking.

Hey Everyone - a few updates on SN20 -

**Highlevel Intro**
**BitAgent (SN20)** leverages LLMs to provide users with natural language control over software.
BitAgent is the go-between from natural language to task orchestration in your applications.

**Best known examples**
BlenderGPT - LLM-integrated operation of the popular Blender3D - <https://github.com/gd3kr/BlenderGPT>
Cadmancer - LLM-driven CAD design - <https://twitter.com/Algomancer/status/1728643892525019602>
Voyager - research paper - LLM-driven minecraft agent - <https://voyager.minedojo.org/>
OS CoPilot - https://os-copilot.github.io/

**What are we doing/working on**
At the production level, we are working integration with near-to-home applications like discord, telegram, VR, twitch/vtuber, web browsers and terminals.
This past weekend, we hosted a telegram bot on top of Subnet 20 in a group with 6000 people from the crypto community.  It was a blast!
We'll show off some demos in the near term.

At the research level, we are exploring and increasing reliability of LLM-engaged task completion, tool usage and overall agent interaction.
Building LLMs into the backbones of companies in a trusted and efficient manner is an ongoing area of research.
We are leveraging the Bittensor subnet to draw upon the skills of the AI community to help us all move past these challenges.

**Near-Term Show and Tells**
2/15 - launched our demos page with a few quick examples
2/17 - scaling test - BitAgent telegram bot launched on 6000-member community channel, among other channels
3/02 - chat-driven, AI vTuber on twitch (was 2/24 - ran into headless OBS and voice cable issues)

1) validators are not validating by trying to get the answer themselves with an LLM like the miners are doing - if that were the case, we'd just give everyone the code and be done (or you'd get it yourself).
2) validators are equipped with an LLM to add randomness to some of the questions.  But are used only as a portion of the overall task design.
3) validators know the ground truth because that is the intended answer, not b/c an LLM said so, but because of how the task was setup

Take the synonyms task as an example - the validator is asked to generated a task for synonyms:
- the validator uses its LLM (mistral) to come up with a random word
- the validator uses its LLM again to come up with a list of synonyms for that random word
- the validator stores the number of words it got above as the number it's looking for - as ground truth
- the validator uses its LLM again to come up with a list of other random words that are not synonyms
- the validator puts the two lists together in random order
- the validator crafts the question
- sends to miners

In this case, it's rare, but it does happen, that the ground truth answer is wrong - i.e., maybe on occasion when the validator uses the LLM to come up with words that are NOT synonyms, it may sneak in an extra synonym b/c LLMs aren't perfect.  If the ground truth is wrong and the miner gets the correct answer - the miner will be penalized - but that's in the rare case and is equally distributed across all miners so should not have a huge impact - this was a risk we were willing to take as of right now.  Although, despite how rare they happen, we are working to never see issues like that in any of our tasks.

This task is not easy for a naive LLM equipped with no tools/logic.  This is one of the first tasks incentivizing those that branch out to use tools with their LLMs.
